<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF : W. HOLLYWOOD CARD CLUB BACKERS LOSE COURT 
BID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Supporters of a proposed West Hollywood city ordinance that would allow a card 
club to be built lost a court bid Friday to have much of an argument opposing 
the measure stricken from the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
Superior Court Judge David Yaffe ruled that such language as "sleazy," "fraud" 
and "scam" must be allowed in the argument opposing the measure because there 
was no "clear and convincing evidence" to show the argument is false. 
</P>
<P>
However, Yaffe ordered the city clerk to strike a portion of the argument that 
alleges other cities that have allowed card clubs to be built experienced more 
crime. Bradley Hertz, a lawyer representing Bruce Decker, who wants to build 
the card club, said he presented statistics to Yaffe showing that crime 
actually declined in the city of Bell when a card club was built there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
