<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRADLEY TO PAY FINE FOR ROLE IN CONTRACT; 
</P>
<P>
SETTLEMENT: MAYOR UNINTENTIONALLY VIOLATED LAW IN AWARDING OF JOB TO A 
CONTRIBUTOR, FPPC SAYS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH CONNELL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley has agreed to pay a $2,000 fine for illegally 
participating in a decision to give a contract to a political contributor, 
state officials announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The settlement, which is expected to be approved by the state Fair Political 
Practices Commission next month, concludes a year-old investigation of 
decisions involving Bradley when he served as chairman of the Los Angeles 
County Transportation Commission in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
The fine is similar to one levied in July against Los Angeles City Councilman 
Michael Woo, who illegally voted to give a political donor a contract while 
serving on the transit panel. 
</P>
<P>
Bradley's fine is a result of failing to properly disclose $1,800 in 
contributions from Gruen Associates, a consulting firm, when he participated in 
a decision to award the firm a contract to study a controversial San Fernando 
Valley trolley line. 
</P>
<P>
The FPPC imposed relatively light fines on Bradley and Woo after concluding 
that their violations were unintentional. The FPPC also found that the 
transportation commission lacked adequate procedures to alert members to 
potential legal conflicts involving contractors. 
</P>
<P>
Bradley spokesman Bill Chandler said that Bradley has "initiated steps to 
rectify this (transportation commission) oversight." 
</P>
<P>
The state Political Reform Act imposes special anti-favoritism requirements on 
commission members, including a ban on voting on matters involving political 
contributors who have given members $250 or more in the previous 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
The investigation began after The Times reported that Bradley and other 
prominent transportation commissioners had collected nearly $600,000 in 
campaign contributions from commission contractors and that, in some cases, the 
state law was being violated. 
</P>
<P>
Bradley and Woo quickly returned nearly $20,000 in contributions from several 
contractors after inquiries from The Times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, BRADLEY FINED: Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley has agreed to pay a $2,000 
fine for his role in awarding a county transportation contract to a campaign 
contributor. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
