<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORST FIRES IN DECADES BURN FRENCH FORESTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOULON, France 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mediterranean winds Friday fanned the flames of France's worst forest fires in 
26 years, killing one person and threatening several towns. 
</P>
<P>
Flames up to 65 feet high have roared out of control, burning more than 32,000 
acres of southern France since Tuesday. A lack of rain and high winds have 
hampered the effort to control the flames. 
</P>
<P>
A long, dry spell and the steep mountain slopes also have made controlling the 
fires difficult for the 2,000 firefighters and the pilots dropping thousands of 
gallons of water on the blazes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA082590-0111 </DOCNO>
